Subsidy trap
Cambridge, USA—No policy pits good economics so directly against good politics as do food and energy subsidies.
Unaffordable subsidies are becoming the core issue facing the three most important new leaders in the world. They are Egyptian President Sisi, Indonesian President "Jokowi" Widodo, and Indian Prime Minister Modi.
The subsidy cuts Sisi faces are turning out to be better than expected.
On the contrary, Modi is facing a situation worse than expected, which could even jeopardize the long-awaited WTO agreement.
The situation Jokowi faces remains unclear.
In July, Sisi accomplished a feat rarely achieved by leaders in North Africa and the Middle East: he significantly cut long-standing energy subsidies, raising prices by 41-78%.
Strangely, there have been almost no protests against it.
Egypt's food subsidy program costs over $5 billion annually and urgently needs reform.
Bread prices have remained so low that they are often used to feed animals.
In the past, efforts by North African countries to cut such subsidies often triggered unrest, even toppling governments.
But the Sisi government seems to be making progress in this area as well.
Bread subsidies have been cut by 13%.
Sisi has no choice.
Even after the subsidy cuts, the current government's budget deficit target for the next fiscal year remains at 10% of GDP (14% without the subsidy cuts).
However, almost no one expected Sisi, who came to power in a turbulent political environment, to act more swiftly than Modi, who swept to the premiership in India with an overwhelming democratic majority in his urgent desire for comprehensive economic reforms.
In Indonesia, Jokowi, who began governing in October, inherited long-standing fuel subsidies amounting to as much as $21 billion annually (20% of government spending), a burden that has already overwhelmed the country.
The outgoing Susilo had already taken a courageous first step a year earlier by raising fuel prices.
Jokowi's advisors have recommended cutting the remaining subsidies, and he has bluntly stated his plan to implement the reductions gradually over four years.
Economists confidently oppose commodity subsidies because agricultural and energy markets are close to perfect competition, with a large number of consumers on the demand side and a large number of producers on the supply side.
In imperfectly competitive sectors, it is the government — not large private monopolies — that is the root.
Critics of the invisible hand point out that self-regulating private markets may fail in various ways.
For example, income inequality and environmental externalities are the two main justifications for government intervention.
Food and fossil fuel subsidies often spark sharp controversy because they are frequently justified under the banners of environmental protection or equality, yet they are actually ineffective for these goals and often have the opposite effect.
Less than 20% of Egypt's food subsidies go to the poor.
In most countries, gasoline subsidies benefit the middle class, while the poor rely on walking or public transportation.
In India, less than 0.1% of the LPG subsidies went to the poorest population, while 52.6% flowed into the pockets of the richest people.
Globally, far less than 20% of fossil fuel subsidies go to the poorest 20% of the population.
Food and energy subsidies can also distort public policy, as evidenced by the Modi government's efforts to protect Indian agricultural subsidies.
In fact, the Modi government's rejection of the WTO compromise has undone the most significant progress made in multilateral trade negotiations over the past decade.
Agricultural subsidies sometimes benefit consumers at the expense of producers, especially in poor countries; while at other times they benefit producers at the expense of consumers, especially in wealthy countries.
India's policy aims to have it both ways.
As a result, India accomplished a feat: it provided wheat to consumers at artificially low prices while simultaneously experiencing oversupply, as farmers could obtain high prices.
Farmers also receive subsidies for agricultural inputs—electricity, water, and fertilizers—at the expense of environmental degradation.
The government purchased large amounts of corrupt rice and wheat, while the small portion allocated to consumers was distributed in a corrupt manner that failed to meet the goal of helping the poor.
The government may continue to maintain subsidies and procurement.
But it knows that this would violate WTO rules.
Since it was impossible to permanently change these rules, Modi simply rejected the Trade Facilitation Agreement that the WTO had eagerly anticipated.
Once subsidies are implemented, they are hard to withdraw.
When world commodity prices rise (as they have over the past decade), citizens accustomed to market-determined domestic prices are more likely to accept the reality that officials cannot shield them from the impact.
But people accustomed to government-determined food and energy prices will demand that the government take responsibility.
This constitutes a strong argument for not implementing subsidies from the outset.
But this does not mean that once subsidies are implemented, maintaining them is necessarily the wisest choice for a shrewd politician.
If the alternative to price increases is shortages or rationing, angry opponents are also likely to erupt.
Similarly, if the widening gap ultimately leads to a greater surge in retail prices, slow-moving leaders are also unlikely to benefit.
In an ideal scenario, other more efficient measures to support low-income populations should be implemented alongside the reduction of food and energy subsidies.
Developing countries have gained considerable experience in effective transfer mechanisms, such as Mexico's conditional cash transfer programs like Progresa-Oportunidades and Brazil's Bolsa Família, as well as technological innovations like India's Unique Identification system.
But some countries are forced to adjust only when a budget crisis hits, and they may not have the funds available for transfer payments to alleviate the hardship.
Shrewd politicians might should implement unpopular adjustments right from the start of their tenure.
Both Jokowi and Sisi have adopted this approach.
Modi, who won a landslide victory in elections under the slogan of market reforms, has now fallen behind.
